bofar wrote:

&gt; --- In junit@y..., &quot;weimar_wann&quot; &lt;weimar_wann@y...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; I&#39;m not quite sure how to pose my question...gotten in a little
&gt; over
&gt; &gt; my head here. Basically, I am writing unit tests for an application
&gt; &gt; that is running on Tomcat 4.xx. Database connectivity is achieved
&gt; &gt; through the use of a DataSource (configured in Tomcat&#39;s server.xml,
&gt; &gt; web.xml). The actual Java classes that I am testing do a JNDI
&gt; lookup
&gt; &gt; on the DataSource to get a connection to the database. The
&gt; connection
&gt; &gt; pooling works just fine while running in the Servlet Container, but
&gt; &gt; my problem is testing through JUnit...does anyone know how to test
&gt; a
&gt; &gt; connection that needs to be run through Tomcat?
&gt;
&gt; Hi Weimar,
&gt;
&gt; I started looking at this problem myself today. Are you are picking
&gt; up your datasource from &quot;javax.naming.InitialContext ()&quot; ?
&gt;
&gt; If so, the solution is to have different initialization sources
&gt; for InitialContext, depending on whether the code is running in
&gt; the Tomcat container, or in a Junit test.
&gt;
&gt; First you need a global flag to indicate whether testing is occuring
&gt; or not. Let&#39;s put it in a class called Testing:
&gt;
&gt; public class Testing {
&gt;
&gt;   private static boolean testing = false;
&gt;
&gt;   public synchronized static void testingOn () {
&gt;      testing = true;
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt;   public static boolean isTestingOn () {
&gt;      return testing;
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Next, in the testcase that needs the database connectivity, set
&gt; testing on in the setup method,
&gt;
&gt;   protected void setup () {
&gt;      Testing.testingOn ();
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt; Now in the code that creates InitialContext(), add the following
&gt; lines,
&gt;
&gt;    InitialContext ctx = new InitialContext ();
&gt;    if (isTestingOn) {
&gt;       DataSource ds = new TestingDataSource ();
&gt;       // Note that dsName should be local dnName used by
&gt;       // this program.
&gt;       ctx.addToEnvironment (&quot;java:comp/env/jdbc/dsName&quot;, ds);
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt; The last thing to do is write the TestingDataSource class that
&gt; implements the DataSource interface. I&#39;m planning to look at that
&gt; this afternoon, if you are interested in a copy, let me know.
&gt;
&gt; Sid Stuart
&gt;
&gt;

